      "rationale": "These methods form a cohesive marker management subsystem that maintains collections of markers organized by layer and index. Extracting them into a MarkerRegistry improves separation of concerns by isolating marker lifecycle management from the broader plotting responsibilities, while providing a clean API for marker operations.",
      "reasoning": "\nStep 1: Primary Responsibility Analysis\nThese methods share a single, well-defined responsibility: managing markers on a chart plot. They provide complete CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete) for both domain and range markers, handling their storage in foreground/background layers, managing change listeners, and coordinating notifications. All methods work exclusively with marker collections and their lifecycle management.\n\nStep 2: Shared Concept/Domain\nAll methods belong to the \"marker management\" domain within charting. They operate on four related data structures (foregroundDomainMarkers, backgroundDomainMarkers, foregroundRangeMarkers, backgroundRangeMarkers) and share common patterns for adding, removing, clearing, and retrieving markers. The concept represents a complete subsystem for marker lifecycle management with layer-based organization.\n\nStep 3: Extraction Benefits\n- Single Responsibility Principle: Isolates marker management from other plot concerns like axes, datasets, and rendering\n- Reduces Complexity: Removes 20+ methods from the XYPlot god class, making it more focused\n- Enhances Testability: Marker operations can be tested independently without plot dependencies\n- Improves Reusability: Marker management logic could be reused by other plot types\n- Better Encapsulation: All marker-related state and behavior is contained in one cohesive unit\n\nStep 4: Design Justification\nThis follows the Extract Class refactoring pattern to separate concerns. The extracted class exhibits high cohesion (all methods manage markers) and can achieve low coupling (minimal dependencies beyond Marker, Layer, and change notification). It represents a classic example of the Single Responsibility Principle - one class, one reason to change.\n",
